FYI: A Message from The West Bridgewater Health Agent Rob Casper, Superintendent Patty Oakley and Town Administrator David Gagne:

Due to COVID-19 and in an abundance of caution, all town and school fields will be closed until further notice, including the track and field at the MSHS on Route 106. Until there is a medical breakthrough or a vaccination specifically for COVID-19, the only way to mitigate the spread of the virus is to social distance. We understand that this is an inconvenience but it is necessary to help flatten the curve.

Thank you for your cooperation

post_text:
FYI: Message from Dr. Oakley Governor Baker just announced during his 3:30 press conference that the state wide school closure will remain in effect until Monday May 4th.
The Department of Elementary and Secondary Education will be putting out more guidance on this extended closing to Superintendents tomorrow.
At this point we will continue the connections with our students through the academic enrichment that our teachers have been providing since last Wednesday.
Our Administrative team will provide updates as we receive more information and guidance from the DESE, DPH and the Governor's office.
This is a challenging time for all of us and I am sure that I speak for all of our faculty, staff and administration that we are extremely disappointed that we cannot be in school with our students. We truly miss each and every one of them! But as the Governor stated, health and safety has to come first. We all have to do our part to "flatten the curve", and social distancing through the closing of schools will help this happen.

post_text:
FYI: School Closure Update Information:

1. Thanks to the support of the WB Food Pantry, families of students eligible for free or reduced-price meals can pick up groceries curbside at the Spring Street School Cafeteria door Tuesday 3/17 between 11am-12pm.

We encourage families to pull up to the curb and not exit your car. Food bags will be brought out to you. No identification is required but we ask that you please RSVP by emailing Anne Marie Grinder at agrinder@wbridgewater.com by 4:00pm today if you have not done so already.

2. If any elementary parent needs to borrow a Chromebook for the duration of the school closure for your child, please contact your building principal via e-mail as soon as possible. Chromebooks will be distributed on Wednesday March 18, 2020 from 9-12 at your child's school building. Please ring the doorbell and someone will bring it out to you.

post_text:
FYI #wbwildcats: Here we go again! There is a threat of inclement weather including snow showers and the possibility of black ice conditions on the roads during tomorrow morning's commute, for which there is the potential of calling a delayed start.
Currently, we are scheduled for an early release in-service day, therefore, a delayed start will not help us.
Since we already have 3 cancellation days and winter has not officially started I hesitate to lose another day if we can get into school with a delayed start.

Therefore, I have decided that IF there needs to be a delayed start due to icy road conditions then there will be NO early release and classes WILL continue into the afternoon. All schools will be dismissed at our regular day dismissal times.

IF, however, the road conditions are ok in the am and we are able to start school on time then the early release day schedule will remain in effect.

I will make the call by 5:30 tomorrow am. Thank you for your understanding and as you can imagine, this is not a part of the job that I will miss!!!

post_text:
FYI #wbwildcats community this is a message from the School Committee:

At tonight’s School Committee meeting, the committee unanimously voted to appoint Mr. Mark Bodwell, Principal of the MSHS, as the next Superintendent of the West Bridgewater Public Schools.

Mr. Bodwell will succeed Dr. Patty Oakley upon her retirement on June 30th 2020, after 15 years in the position.

Mr. Bodwell has served the West Bridgewater Public Schools in the capacity of teacher, coach, assistant principal, and principal of both the Howard and Middle Senior High School. For over 20 years, Mr. Bodwell has shown consistent support of West Bridgewater students, families and staff, along with a willingness to work tirelessly for the growth and well-being of the district. The Committee is unanimous in their belief that Mr. Bodwell has all of the skills and qualifications to be a successful superintendent, and is by far the best person to make our already great school system an even better one.

post_text: FYI: This afternoon bus 6 was in a traffic accident on Route 28 near A1 Affordable transporting students from RLM. No one was hurt and all students on board and the driver are safe. The accident appears to be the fault of a white pick-up moving into the lane of the oncoming bus. The bus driver swerved to get out of the way of the truck so that there was less of an impact when the truck hit the bus. All children were removed from the bus and kept safe as emergency responders arrived. Principals arrived at the scene immediately and helped comfort the children until a new bus arrived to take them to the Spring Street School. Each child's parents were contacted and are picking their children up at the school after being checked out by the school nurse. I want to thank our #wbwildcats emergency responders, Principals, office staff, Nurse Idell, SRO and Will Lucini for their quick and organized response, and especially Bus driver Mr. Tom for his quick thinking and putting the safety of our students first at all times.

Meet Sarah Croteau:
Current Position: School Psychologist at the Howard School
I went to Northeastern for both my undergraduate and graduate degrees. I previously worked in Concord, MA at a K-5 school. Prior to working in schools I worked as a counselor in an inpatient therapeutic milieu.
I enjoy photography, kayaking, any art or craft activity, and traveling.
I chose to work in West Bridgewater because it is a growing district. This job allows me to complete assessments and advocate for kids while leaving me with plenty of time to run counseling groups and meet with students individually. I have loved working in West Bridgewater so far. I have been very well supported and encouraged to try new things within my work.

Welcome Aboard Sarah glad you chose to be a Wildcat!

post_text:
Meet our new
Speech/Language Pathologist, Megan Pellisier:
I’m originally from Long Island, New York. I moved up to Massachusetts to attend Boston College and decided to stay! I went on to complete my Master’s Degree at Emerson College. Before coming to West Bridgewater, I worked in Walpole at Fisher Elementary School.

Most of my time outside of school is spent with my son Luke, who is 6 months old. He’s becoming more active each day! Prior to Luke’s arrival, my husband and I enjoyed spending time exploring Boston and traveling to other cities whenever possible. We are looking forward to more adventures with Luke in the future.

I love the tight-knit community feel of West Bridgewater and the great sense of pride everyone has in the district. The staff, students, and families across the district have been extremely warm and welcoming. I’m looking forward to getting to know everyone better over the course of this year!

Welcome aboard Megan we are so happy you chose to become a Wildcat!

post_text:
#WBwildcats "Lead the Way" during STEM week

West Bridgewater Sophomores have been participating in STEM Week-Project Lead the Way sponsored by the Mass STEM Hub, October 21-25. Students have been engaged in a real-world problem-solving adventure tackling the issue of managing and disposal of e-waste. Students worked towards understanding the scope of electronics usage in our daily lives, exploring electronic waste and ecotoxicology, and practicing systems thinking to consider how we can promote a more sustainable product life cycle.

Students were arranged in research teams with assigned roles in order to produce several different work products associated with e-waste. Each research team contained a project manager, recorder, presenter,and quality assurance person. Teams either produced a social media campaign to create awareness or organized an e-waste community disposal drive.

Top proposals will be chosen and submitted for review by STEM professionals and sustainability experts. Top proposals will also be made public on the web through the school website in the coming weeks.

Meet Leah O'Bryan one of our new teachers:
Current Position:
7th and 8th grade English
I graduated from Bridgewater State University, and am from Rockland, MA and went to Rockland High School. I subbed in a few south shore towns and taught English in Cambodia for 4 months and during the summer I am assistant director of a local Summer camp.

Special Interests or hobbies: As an English teacher I love reading and writing, but also love sports, hiking, hanging out with my family and friends and traveling.

Why I chose West Bridgewater to work in:
West Bridgewater is a great district, with an amazing administration across the board who supports you.

Your initial thoughts of teaching in West Bridgewater: I long-term subbed last year and loved working here and was excited to dive back in with other teachers who support their students and support one another. I love it!

Welcome Aboard Leah, we are so glad you chose to become a Wildcat!

post_text: FYI: I just recently got off the phone with Lucini's and they have assured me that the current driver on bus 1 will NOT be driving for us tomorrow or in the future. There will be a sub driver tomorrow which unfortunately could cause additional delays, but please know that I truly understand your frustrations and anger with the situation and that I am working with Lucini's to find a suitable permanent driver as soon as possible, so we can remedy this problem.

post_text: FYI as you may have heard there have been major delays with Bus 1 this week after the regular bus driver quit on Monday. This morning the replacement driver didn't show up to work and a sub driver was not found until 8am, which is when we were notified of the problem. The bus is going through the Howard route to pick up any remaining riders and continuing on to RLM and Spring. I apologize for the inconveniences this is causing and am working with Lucinis to remedy the situation asap, along with receiving more timely communications from them on issues such as these.

post_text: FYI #wbwildcats: Based on the latest report from the NWS and other local forecasts there is a high probability of a significant amount of heavy wet plowable snow overnight in the WB area. In order for parents to have ample time to plan for childcare etc. I am going to make the call this evening to cancel school tomorrow March 4, 2019. Although it's New England in March and weather has the potential to change overnight with all of the information I have right now I believe this is the right decision.

post_text:
FYI #wbwildcats As I'm sure you are aware, local forecasts are calling for some overnight snow in our region. Currently, it is predicted to be a light and fluffy 3-5 inches stopping in the early dawn hours. As we all know, it is New England weather and forecasts can change last minute. Therefore, after speaking with the WB DPW, we have decided to wait until tomorrow morning to make any decision on an on-time start, late start, or cancellation. The call will be made by 5:30 AM.

My Gnomes are ready for action!

post_text: FYI #wbwildcats: Due to the current track and timing of the storm predicted by local forecasters to impact our region, there will be a 2-hour early dismissal for all West Bridgewater Public Schools tomorrow Tuesday, February 12th. The following dismissal times will be in effect; MSHS 12 noon, Howard and Spring 12:30 pm, RLM 1:00 pm. Lunch will be served at all schools prior to dismissal. Surround Care and all other after-school activities will be canceled. Thank you and have a good evening.
